Let’s use the other variables to predict bill_depth_mm. Prepare your data and fit the following models on a training dataset subset of the entire dataset:

  • Four different models, each containing a different set of predictor variables

Create a plot like the right plot of Fig 1. in our Model Validation chapter with the training and test error plotted for each of your four models.

Which of your models was best?

Code 
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
from sklearn.compose import ColumnTransformer
from sklearn.preprocessing import OneHotEncoder
from sklearn.pipeline import Pipeline
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error

penguins = load_penguins()
Code 
from plotnine import *

models = {
    "Model 1": ["bill_length_mm"],
    "Model 2": ["bill_length_mm", "flipper_length_mm"],
    "Model 3": ["bill_length_mm", "flipper_length_mm", "body_mass_g"],
    "Model 4": ["bill_length_mm", "flipper_length_mm", "body_mass_g", "species", "island", "sex"],
}

y = "bill_depth_mm"

train_df, test_df = train_test_split(
    penguins, test_size=0.30, random_state=42, stratify=penguins["species"]
)

num = ["bill_length_mm", "flipper_length_mm", "body_mass_g"]
cat = ["species", "island", "sex"]

rows = []
summary_rows = []

#Used Chat to iterate this so it would be streamline
for name, feats in models.items():
    # Split features into numeric and categorical
    numeric_feats = [c for c in feats if c in num]
    categ_feats = [c for c in feats if c in cat]

    # Handle train/test separately but use same dummy columns
    X_tr = train_df[feats].copy()
    X_te = test_df[feats].copy()

    # One-hot encode categoricals
    X_tr = pd.get_dummies(X_tr, columns=categ_feats)
    X_te = pd.get_dummies(X_te, columns=categ_feats)

    # Align columns so train and test match
    X_te = X_te.reindex(columns=X_tr.columns, fill_value=0)

    y_tr = train_df[y]
    y_te = test_df[y]

    # Fit linear regression
    model = LinearRegression()
    model.fit(X_tr, y_tr)

    pred_tr = model.predict(X_tr)
    pred_te = model.predict(X_te)

    rows.append(pd.DataFrame({
        "Actual": np.concatenate([y_tr.values, y_te.values]),
        "Predicted": np.concatenate([pred_tr, pred_te]),
        "Dataset": ["Train"] * len(y_tr) + ["Test"] * len(y_te),
        "Model": name
    }))

    tr_rmse = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_tr, pred_tr))
    te_rmse = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_te, pred_te))
    summary_rows.append({"Model": name, "Train RMSE": tr_rmse, "Test RMSE": te_rmse})

# Combine results
plot_df = pd.concat(rows, ignore_index=True)
summary_df = pd.DataFrame(summary_rows).set_index("Model").sort_index()
best_model = summary_df["Test RMSE"].idxmin()

print(summary_df.round)

# Plot results
plot = (
    ggplot(plot_df, aes(x="Actual", y="Predicted", color="Dataset"))
    + geom_point(alpha=0.6)
    + geom_smooth(method="lm", se=False, linetype="dashed", color="black")
    + geom_abline(slope=1, intercept=0, linetype="dotted")
    + facet_wrap("~Model")
    + theme_minimal()
    + labs(
        title="Actual vs Predicted Bill Depth (mm) Across Four Models",
        x="Actual bill_depth_mm",
        y="Predicted bill_depth_mm",
        color="Dataset"
    )
)

plot
